1. Introduction

Social economic development significantly influences the quality of life of residents in a country or region. Therefore, it is important to understand different indicators of social economic development in a country to comprehensively evaluate the development levels across different regions and determine the crucial factors which contribute to their development disparities. The policy makers will be able to use these analyses as reference to formulate regional development plans and policies.

Peru is a developing country located in South America. Using the district level census data from Peru and multivariate analysis techniques, I aim at determining the major contributors of the differences in development levels.

2. Design, Primary Questions, and Planned analyses

  • Design: In this study, I will use the key socioeconomic variables in a census conducted in Peru and conducted several multivariate analyses to understand the contribution of the variables to the socioeconomic disparity in different districts.

  • Question 1: Can we translate multiple socioeconomic indicators into a few interpretable components?

    • Planned analysis: Principal component analysis (PCA)

  • Question 2: How can we differentiate regions with varying levels of social development based on a set of socioeconomic indicators?

    • Planned analysis: Discriminant Analysis (DA)

  • Question 3: Are the multivariate means different in different groups of districts?

    • Planned analysis: Multivariate analysis of variance (MANOVA)

  • Question 4: Are there cluster of variables which move on similar directions?

    • Planned analysis: Cluster analysis for variables

3. Data source and description of variables

The database I use is a census data in Peru. The census data have a variety of demographical and social economic parameters (https://censos2017.inei.gob.pe/redatam/). I discussed with Dr. Reuning-Scherer and used the following variables in the final project:

ubigeo (character): District number (district ID)

idh (numeric): Human development index

monetary_poverty (numeric): Proportion of people meeting the criteria of poverty

life_expectancy (numeric): Life expectancy

complete_secondary_edu (numeric): Proportion of people complete secondary education 70%-90%

years_edu (numeric): Average years of education

family_income (numeric): Average family income

number_hh (numeric): Number of households participating in the census

hh_1_nbi_or_more (numeric): Number of households with one or more unmet need (Before data wrangling)/ Proportion of family with 1 or more unmet need (After data wrangling)

hh_wo_sanitation (numeric): Number of households without sanitation (Before data wrangling)/ Proportion of households without sanitation (After data wrangling)

Note: The categorical variables required for discriminant analysis and MANOVA will be created in the corresponding parts (7.1 and 8.1).

4. Data wrangling

During the discussion of the dataset with Dr. Reuning-Scherer, he suggested me to convert the variables related to number of household into proportion. The number of household participating in the census is used as denominators and is removed after the proportions are calculated. Also, he suggested it was better not to include many codes in the report. So the codes were not shown in most parts of the report for the purpose of conciseness. There is a html version with all the codes in my github page https://github.com/dwingspixel563/Final-project-S-DS-563 for your reference.

data1 <- read.csv('data/data_census.csv')

6. Multivariate analysis 1: Principal Component Analysis

6.1 Preparation for PCA

6.1.1 Multivariate normal distribution check

Though PCA does not require multivariate normal distribution, parallel analysis requires the multivariate normal distribution. Therefore, I have a look at the multivariate chi-square quantile plot of my data.

cqplot(data1[,-1])

After discussion with Dr. Reuning-Scherer, I tried logit transformation of the proportions and idh (which are between 0-1), and do log transformation to other variables, to see whether it will improve the multivariate normal distribution of my data

data2 <- data1 %>%  
  mutate_at(vars(c("idh","monetary_poverty", "complete_secondary_edu", 
"hh_1_nbi_or_more", "hh_wo_sanitation")),
function(x) car::logit(x,adjust = 0.025)) %>% 
mutate_at(vars(c( "life_expectancy", "years_edu", "family_income")), function(x) log(x))

cqplot(data2[,-1])

It seems that the multivariate chi-square quantile plots are similar before and after transformation. If the data follow the multivariate normal distribution, the chi-square quantile plots will fit a line. But my data seem not fit a line very well. Therefore, my data do not seem to follow multivariate normal distribution very well. Dr. Reuning-Scherer suggested it would still be useful to have a look at the parallel analysis result, so I would give it a try in the later part. As the data transformation does not help to improve the multivariate normality, I will use the original data.

6.1.2 Correlation of the variables

chart.Correlation(data1[, -1])

I feel that PCA will work well on my data. PCA requires linear correlation between variables and will work better when variables are correlated. Most of my data are correlated and most of the correlations are linear.

6.2.1 Total variance explained by a given number of principal components

The Comp.1 explains ~55% variance, adding Comp.2 explains a cumulative ~ 72% variance, and adding Comp.3 explains ~85% variance. If I set 70% threshold, Comp.1 and Comp.2 will be retained. If I set 80% threshold, Comp.1, Comp.2, and Comp.3 will be retained.

Comp.1 seems to be driven by human development index(idh, 0.46), poverty proportion (monetary_poverty, -0.40), proportion of completing secondary education (complete_secondary_edu, 0.35), years of education (years_edu, 0.43) and family income (family_income, 0.43). The Comp.1 seems to represent the wealthy level of the district. While family income is the direct measure of wealth, human development index, education year and complete_secondary_edu are indirect measures of wealth. The direction of Comp.1 is pointing towards higher wealth, as idh, years_edu, family_income has positive value, while monetary_poverty has negative value.

Comp.2 seems to be driven by hh_1_nbi_or_more (proportion of family with 1 or more unmet need, 0.62) and hh_wo_sanitation (proportion of family without sanitation, 0.68). Comp.2 seems to represent living conditions, as these two measures are the living conditions of the households. The direction of comp.2 points towards lower living condition, as both hh_1_nbi_or_more and hh_wo_sanitation have positive value.

Comp.2 is mainly driven by hh_1_nbi_or_more and hh_wo_sanitation. 6.5 Summary of PCA

In summary, the PCA reduces the dimensions of my data from 8 to 2. The two principal components are: 1. Wealth of the district: driven by human development index, proportion of completing secondary education, years of education and family income, and also a variable on the other direction (poverty proportion); 2. Living conditions of the district: driven by hh_1_nbi_or_more (proportion of family with 1 or more unmet need) and hh_wo_sanitation (proportion of family without sanitation). Most of the variability of the data (>70%) can be explained by the wealth and living condition of the district.

Also, according to the biplot above, the two principal components well represent the directions of the variables. We can easily identify two groups of variables. There are some outliers in higher dimensional spaces according to the scoreplot, but I feel they are mainly due to the distribution of the data are not multivariate normal. We have 1874 observations for 8 variables. The sample size is big enough for PCA.

7. Multivariate analysis 2: Discriminant Analysis

7.1 Data wrangling

For the purpose of discriminant analysis, I create a new categorical variable based on Human development index (HDI): HDI of less than 0.400 for low human development, 0.400–0.599 for medium human development, 0.600 or greater for high human development. The new variable is hdi_cat. The purpose of this category is to measure the relative development level within the country, so the category is based on the distribution of HDI within Peru and it is different from the HDI category criteria by UNDP. For the purpose of this analysis, as complete_secondary_edu is very relevant to years_edu and may compete in the DA model, I choose years_edu and remove complete_secondary_edu.

The number of district in each category in the hdi_cat variable is as follows:

data_da <- data1 %>% mutate(hdi_cat = case_when(idh <0.400 ~ "low",
                                              idh >=0.400 & idh <0.600 ~ 'medium',
                                              idh >=0.600 ~ 'high'),
                          hdi_cat = fct_relevel(hdi_cat, "low", "medium", "high")) %>%
dplyr::select(-complete_secondary_edu)

table(data_da$hdi_cat, useNA = 'always')

After trying the combinations of several different variables, it seems that the different groups do have similar foot prints in the plots. As I have a large database (n > 1000), Box’s M test is too sensitive and always result in significant P value and reject the null hypothesis. Therefore, for my data, Box’s M test may not be reliable. Considering the similarity in foot prints in the plots and the large sample size, Dr. Reuning-Scherer suggested me to use linear DA, so I use linear DA in the later analyses.

Considering the matrix plots and the proportion variables will have huge impact on the multivariate normality, after discussing with Dr. Reuning-Scherer, I decided to only include non-proportion variables (years_edu, life_expectancy and family_income) in the DA.

7.4 Summary of DA

DA requires multivariate normal distribution within each group. After several attempts in 7.2 part and discussion with Dr. Reuning-Scherer, I decided to only include non-proportion variables (years_edu, life_expectancy and family_income) in the DA to meet the assumption of DA. According to the characteristic of my data, linear DA is better to be used.

From stepwise discriminant analysis, there is only 1 variable (family outcome) retained, I add another (years_edu) in the lda according to Dr. Reuning-Scherer’s suggestion. The DA functions based on family outcome and years_edu work very well in separating the groups of different HDI level. The variables have a 91% correct percent for prediction.

8. Multivariate analysis 3: MANOVA

8.1 Data wrangling

For the purpose of two-way MANOVA, I create two categorical variables: (1)hdi_cat: based on Human development index (HDI): HDI of less than 0.400 for low human development, 0.400–0.599 for medium human development, 0.600 or greater for high human development. The purpose of this category is to measure the relative development level within the country, so the category is based on the hdi within Peru and it is different from the HDI category criteria by UNDP. This variable is the same as what I used in discriminant analysis. (2)complete_secondary_edu_cat: based on complete_secondary_edu: low: < 40% of people complete secondary education; medium: 40% to <70% of people complete secondary education; high: >=70% of people complete secondary education. As complete_secondary_edu is very relevant to years_edu and may compete in the model, I remove years_edu.

I will use monetary_poverty, life_expectancy and family_income as response variables for the MANOVA from 8.2 to 8.4, and reserve hh_1_nbi_or_more and hh_wo_sanitation for additional predicting variables to be added in the model in 8.5.

data1 <- read.csv('data/data_census.csv')

data_manova <- data1 %>% mutate(hh_1_nbi_or_more = hh_1_nbi_or_more/number_hh,
                          hh_wo_sanitation = hh_wo_sanitation/number_hh,
                          hdi_cat = case_when(idh <0.400 ~ "low HDI",
                                              idh >=0.400 & idh <0.600 ~ 
                                                'medium HDI',
                                              idh >=0.600 ~ 'high HDI'),
                          hdi_cat = fct_relevel(hdi_cat, "low HDI", 
                                                "medium HDI", "high HDI"),
                          complete_secondary_edu_cat = case_when(
                            complete_secondary_edu <0.4 ~ "low EDU",
                            complete_secondary_edu >=0.4 & 
                              complete_secondary_edu <0.7 ~ 'medium EDU',
                            complete_secondary_edu >=0.7 ~ 'high EDU'),
                          complete_secondary_edu_cat = 
                            fct_relevel(complete_secondary_edu_cat,
                                        "low EDU", 
                                        "medium EDU", 
                                        "high EDU" )) %>%
dplyr::select(-number_hh, -complete_secondary_edu, -idh, -years_edu)

monetary_poverty, life_expectancy and family_income are in different scales, I consulted with Dr. Reuning-Scherer and got information that it was not necessary to convert the data to be in the same scale, as the conversion will not change the result. So I did not change the scale of the data.

In the first plot for monetary_poverty, the lines at low HDI level and medium HDI level are almost parallel to each other, while the high HDI line shows a different pattern. Therefore, there might be some interactions between the HDI category and Complete secondary education category’s effects on monetary_poverty, and the interaction mainly happens at the high HDI level. Specifically, the low EDU & high HDI group has higher poverty proportion than expected.

In the second plot for life_expectancy, the lines at low HDI level and medium HDI level are almost parallel to each other, while the high HDI line shows a different pattern. Therefore, there might be some interactions between the HDI category and Complete secondary education category’s effects on life_expectancy, and the interaction also mainly happens at the high HDI level. Specifically, the low EDU & high HDI group has higher life expectancy than expected.

In the third plot for family_income, the lines at low HDI level, medium HDI level and high HDI level are almost all parallel to each other. Therefore, it seems that there is minimal to no interaction between the HDI category and Complete secondary education category’s effects on family_income.

The significance level I set is 0.05. According to the two-way MANOVA (multivariate result), complete_secondary_edu_cat and hdi_cat both have significant main effects on our response variables, as shown by P < 0.001 in all the different measures (Pillai, Wilks, Hotelling-Lawley, Roy). For the interaction effects, only Roy measure shows significant result (0.02), and all other measures are not significant. Therefore, I do not think there is enough confidence to say that there is a interaction effect between complete_secondary_edu_cat and hdi_cat on our response variables (monetary_poverty, life_expectancy and family_income).

The univariate results are different depending on whether I use Type I sum of squares or Type III sum of squares. If I use Type I sum of squares, both complete_secondary_edu_cat and hdi_cat have significant individual effects on all three response variables in univariate analysis, while the interaction effects in the three univariate analyses are all not significant. If I use Type III sum of squares, the complete_secondary_edu_cat’s main effect lost significance for family_income, which the interaction of complete_secondary_edu_cat and hdi_cat gained siginificance for monetary_poverty. Other results are similar.

8.4 Multivariate contrasts

To do contracts I need to convert a two-way problem into a one-way problem, so first I create an interaction variable which has all combinations of complete_secondary_edu_cat and hdi_cat and then run the analysis in different combinations of the two categorical variables.

As there are regression formulas in this part. I also include codes here.

8.5 Add a continuous variable to my model and fit as a multiple-response linear model

As can be seen from the correlation plot below, the association of hh_wo_sanitation and hh_1_nbi_or_more, and the 3 response variables is weakly linear. I discussed with Dr. Reuning-Scherer and he considered such relationship is acceptable to be added to the model. It seems that hh_wo_sanitation has a relatively more linear relationship with the three response variables. So I add hh_wo_sanitation to the model.

8.7 Summary of MANOVA

In this part, I first investigated the potential interaction of the two categorical variables on the 3 continuous variables by doing interaction plots. And the plots showed that there might be some interaction effects on monetary_poverty and life_expectancy, but the interaction is minimal on family_income.

Then I did two-way ANOVA with monetary_poverty, life_expectancy and family_income as response variables and hdi_cat (HDI category) and complete_secondary_edu_cat (Education category) as categorical predicting variables. According to the two-way MANOVA (multivariate result), complete_secondary_edu_cat and hdi_cat both have significant main effects on our response variables, as shown by P < 0.001 in all the different measures (Pillai, Wilks, Hotelling-Lawley, Roy). However, there is not strong evidence of an interaction effect between complete_secondary_edu_cat and hdi_cat on the response variables. The univariate results varied by whether Type I sum of squares or Type III sum of squares was used.

Next, I tried multivariate and univariate contrasts, which again supported the difference in different levels of HDI and education. Then I tried to add a continuous variable to the manova model to make it multiple response linear model. The main effects and interaction effect of the two categorical variables are both significant in the new model.I also tried MRPP test, which showed different multivariate means in HDI categories, education categories, combinations of the two categories.

In summary, there is strong evidence that the multivariate means of different HDI categories and education categories are different. Whether there is significant interaction effect of the two categorical variables depends on the models and methods.

9.2.2 Group diagnostic function: cluster variables

source("http://reuningscherer.net/multivariate/R/HClusEval3.R.txt")

hclus_eval <- function(data_m, dist_m = 'euclidean', clus_m = 'ward', plot_op = T, dist_cust = NA, print_num = NA, title){
  
  output_list <- list()
  
  ## Some Initial Calculations
  
 ### END INITIAL CALCULATIONS
  
  ### Create Distance matrix and Clustering ###
  Info <- paste('Creating Distance Matrix using', dist_m)
 # print(Info)
  
    if (dist_m == 'custom' & !is.na(dist_cust)) {dist1 <- dist_cust} 
    else dist1 <- dist(data_m, method= dist_m)

  
  Info <- paste('Clustering using', clus_m)
#  print(Info)
  
  clust1 <- hclust(dist1, method = clus_m)
 
#  print('Clustering Complete. Access the Cluster object in first element of output')
  
  output_list[[1]] <- clust1
  
  
  rs_out <- affected.rows(clust1$merge)
  
  me <- gen_cutmat(clust1, dim(data_m)[1])
  rs <- rs_out[[2]]

  # Calculate Metrics #
  
  output_list[[2]] <- RMSSTD_FUNC(data_m, rs, dim(data_m)[1])

  output_list[[3]] <- RSQ_FUNC(data_m, me, dim(data_m)[1])

  output_list[[4]] <- SPRS_FUNC(data_m, rs, dim(data_m)[1], me)

  output_list[[5]] <- cluster.dis(data_m, clust1, output_list[[4]])

  #ylim_n <- max(output_list[[2]], output_list[[3]], output_list[[4]], output_list[[5]])
  ylim_n <- max(output_list[[2]], output_list[[3]], output_list[[4]])

  if (plot_op == T){
    print_len <- rep(print_num, 5)
    if (is.na(print_num)) {
       for (i in 1:5) {print_len[i] <- length(output_list[[i]])}
    }
    plot(output_list[[3]][1:print_len[3]], type = 'l', col = 'red', ylim = c(0, ylim_n), lwd=3, main = title)
    lines(output_list[[2]][1:print_len[2]], col = 'blue', lwd=3)
    lines(output_list[[4]][1:print_len[4]], col = 'green', lwd=3)
    #lines(output_list[[5]][1:print_len[5]], col = 'black', lwd=3)
    legend('topright', c('RSQ', 'RMSSTD', 'SPRSQ'), lty = c(1 ,1,1),
      col = c('red', 'blue', 'green'))
    #Plot CD
   
   
  }



}

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))

kdata <- data_cs_t
n.lev <- 5  #set max value for number of clusters k

# Calculate the within groups sum of squared error (SSE) for the number of cluster solutions selected by the user
wss <- rnorm(3)
while (prod(wss==sort(wss,decreasing=T))==0) {
  wss <- (nrow(kdata)-1)*sum(apply(kdata,2,var))
  for (i in 2:n.lev) wss[i] <- sum(kmeans(kdata, centers=i)$withinss)}

# Calculate the within groups SSE for 250 randomized data sets (based on the original input data)
k.rand <- function(x){
  km.rand <- matrix(sample(x),dim(x)[1],dim(x)[2])
  rand.wss <- as.matrix(dim(x)[1]-1)*sum(apply(km.rand,2,var))
  for (i in 2:n.lev) rand.wss[i] <- sum(kmeans(km.rand, centers=i)$withinss)
  rand.wss <- as.matrix(rand.wss)
  return(rand.wss)
}

rand.mat <- matrix(0,n.lev,250)

k.1 <- function(x) { 
  for (i in 1:250) {
    r.mat <- as.matrix(suppressWarnings(k.rand(kdata)))
    rand.mat[,i] <- r.mat}
  return(rand.mat)
}

# Same function as above for data with < 3 column variables
k.2.rand <- function(x){
  rand.mat <- matrix(0,n.lev,250)
  km.rand <- matrix(sample(x),dim(x)[1],dim(x)[2])
  rand.wss <- as.matrix(dim(x)[1]-1)*sum(apply(km.rand,2,var))
  for (i in 2:n.lev) rand.wss[i] <- sum(kmeans(km.rand, centers=i)$withinss)
  rand.wss <- as.matrix(rand.wss)
  return(rand.wss)
}

9.4 Summary of cluster analysis

From the analyses above, I think 2 or 4 clusters exist among variables (4 is more likely). The hierarchical diagnostic functions in 9.2.2 show that it is likely 2 or 4 clusters exist, while the k-means SSE plot shows around 4 clusters are more likely.

As there are many ways of doing the cluster in hierarchical clustering and they are very similar, I discussed with Dr. Reuning-Scherer and he thinks it is ok to use one of them here. I will use euclidean distance with average linkage as an example to summarize the clusters.

For hierarchical cluster, the final clusters (4 cluster version) are: cluster 1: life_expectancy; cluster 2: complete_secondary_edu, years_edu, idh, family_income; cluster 3: monetary_poverty; cluster 4: hh_1_nbi_or_more, hh_wo_sanitation.

And the 4-cluster version for k-means cluster is similar: cluster 1: idh, life_expectancy, family_income; cluster 2: hh_1_nbi_or_more, hh_wo_sanitation; cluster 3: complete_secondary_edu, years_edu; cluster 4: monetary_poverty.

It seems that the household characteristics are clustered together (hh_1_nbi_or_more, hh_wo_sanitation). Also, the economic factors such as idh and family income are also clustered together. The education variables are also tending to be clustered together (complete_secondary_edu, years_edu). There are all making sense to me.

10. Discussion and conclusion

In this report, I used several multivariate analytical methods to explore the Peru socioeconomic database and identified the patterns of the variables.

In principal component analysis, I successfully reduced the dimensions of the data from 8 to 2. The two principal components are wealth of the district and living conditions of the district. The two principal components explained more than 70% variability of the data, and provided a more concise and interpretable landscape of the socioeconomic status of different districts. In the future, the policymakers may want to improve the well-being of people by working on these two perspectives.

In discriminant analysis, I found that the DA functions based on family outcome and years of education work very well in separating the groups of different HDI level. This finding can serve as the basis to construct a easy-to-conduct algorithm to predict the HDI level. The finding also highlight some areas to work on to improve the HDI level.

In MANOVA, I found that the multivariate means of monetary_poverty, life_expectancy and family_income in different HDI and education groups are different. Whether there is interaction between HDI and education groups depends on the methods used. This indicates the potential influence of HDI and education on other metrics of socioeconomic status.

In cluster analysis for variables, I found 4 clusters of variables, which again indicates different aspects of socioeconomic status. The cluster of variables also reflect the result of principal components in PCA, and the result of DA. For example, living conditions (hh_1_nbi_or_more and hh_wo_sanitation) are clustered together, corresponding to the second principal component in PCA. Also, education variables are clustered together, reflecting the result of DA that education is a important contribute to predict HDI level.

In summary, by applying several multiplevariate analysis methods, I found that education level, living conditions, and wealth are major drivers of socioeconomic status. It is important to understand the interplay between these factors and promote social welfare and equity.
